  "prompt": "U.S. Immigration: Can an H1-B visa be extended by future employers beyond 6 years based on an approved I-140 through the previous employer?",
  "response": "Yes, under certain conditions, an H1-B visa holder can extend their stay beyond the standard 6-year limit if they have an approved I-140 petition. This is known as an H1-B visa extension under AC21 (American Competitiveness in the 21st Century Act).\n\nKey conditions:\n1. An I-140 immigrant petition must be approved\n2. The H1-B visa holder is either:\n- Waiting for an immigrant visa number to become available\n- Cannot file adjustment of status or complete immigrant visa processing due to per-country visa number limitations\n\nA new employer can continue to extend the H1-B visa in one-year increments until:\n- Green card is obtained\n- I-140 petition is withdrawn\n- Priority date becomes current and the individual can complete immigration processing\n\nThe extension is typically granted in one-year increments, providing continued work authorization while waiting for permanent residency.\n\nIt's recommended to consult an immigration attorney for specific details, as individual circumstances can vary and immigration regulations are complex.",
